<body>
<p>In this article, Maria Daskalaki connects the practical concept of cosmopolitanism with the academic research on global careers. She does so in a unique way by her own experiences as a cosmopolitan via the use of autoethnography and autobiography. This article is interesting, not only because of the fascinating insights gained from the empirical research, but also because it provides a very clear understanding of the use of autoethnography as a method in organizational studies. I think this work does an excellent job of continuing the tradition within <italic>Journal of Management Inquiry</italic> (<italic>JMI</italic>) of having scholars take them and their work more purposely, and eliminating the chasm between researcher and research (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1056492612455141">Empson, in press</xref>).</p>
